6 An Act relating to professions and occupations;
amending 59 O.S. 2021, Section 698.2, which relates
7 to veterinary profession definitions; modifying
certain definitions; providing for new definitions;
8 and providing an effective date.
9
10
11 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
12 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 698.2, is
13 amended to read as follows:
14 Section 698.2. As used in the Oklahoma Veterinary Practice
15 Act:
16 1. "Board" means the State Board of Veterinary Medical
17 Examiners;
18 2. "Animal" means any animal other than humans and includes,
19 but is not limited to, fowl, fish, birds and reptiles, wild or
20 domestic, living or dead;
21 3. "Veterinarian" means a person who has received a degree in
22 veterinary medicine or its equivalent from a school of veterinary
23 medicine;
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 1

1 4. "Licensed veterinarian" means any veterinarian who holds an
2 active license to practice veterinary medicine in this state;
3 5. "School of veterinary medicine" means any veterinary college
4 or division of a university or college that offers the degree of
5 doctor of veterinary medicine or its equivalent, which conforms to
6 the standards required for accreditation by the American Veterinary
7 Medical Association (AVMA) and which is recognized and approved by
8 the Board;
9 6. "Veterinary technician" means a person who has graduated
10 from a program accredited by the American Veterinary Medical
11 Association, or its equivalent which is recognized and approved by
12 the Board, and who has passed the examination requirements set forth
13 by the Board, and is certified to practice under the direct
14 supervision of a licensed veterinarian. For the purpose of the
15 Oklahoma Veterinary Practice Act, "registered veterinary technician
16 (RVT)" will be used interchangeably with veterinary technician who
17 is certified pursuant to Sections 698.21 through 698.26 of this
18 title;
19 7. "Veterinary technologist" means a person who has
20 successfully graduated from an AVMA-accredited bachelor degree
21 program of veterinary technology, or its AVMA equivalent;
22 8. "Veterinary assistant" means an individual who may perform
23 the duties of a veterinary technician or veterinary technologist;
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 2

1 howe ver, has not graduated from an AVMA-accredited technology
2 program or its equivalent, and has not been certified by the Board;
3 9. "Veterinary technology" means the science and art of
4 providing all aspects of professional medical care, services and
5 treatment for animals with the exception of diagnosis, prognosis,
6 surgery and prescription of any treatments, drugs, medications or
7 appliances, where a valid veterinarian-client-patient relationship
8 exists;
9 10. "Direct supervision" means:
10 a. directions have been given to a veterinary technician,
11 nurse, laboratory technician, intern, veterinary
12 assistant or other employee for medical care following
13 the examination of an animal by the licensed
14 veterinarian responsible for the professional care of
15 the animal, or
16 b. that, under certain circumstances following the
17 examination of an animal by a licensed veterinarian
18 responsible for the professional care of the animal,
19 the presence of the licensed veterinarian on the
20 premises in an animal hospital setting or in the same
21 general area in a range setting is required after
22 directions have been given to a veterinarian who has a
23 certificate issued pursuant to Section 698.8 of this
24 title;
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 3

1 11. "License" means authorization to practice veterinary
2 medicine granted by the Board to an individual found by the Board to
3 meet certain requirements pursuant to the Oklahoma Veterinary
4 Practice Act or any other applicable statutes;
5 12. "Supervised Doctor of Veterinary Medicine Certificate"
6 means authorization to practice veterinary medicine with certain
7 limitations or restrictions on that practice, set by the Board or
8 authorization to perform certain enumerated functions peripheral to
9 the practice of veterinary medicine as set by the Board and has a
10 certificate issued pursuant to Section 698.8 of this title;
11 13. "Veterinarian-client-patient relationship" means when:
12 a. the licensed veterinarian has assumed the
13 responsibility for making medical judgments regarding
14 the health of an animal or animals and the need for
15 medical treatment, and the client, owner or other
16 caretaker has agreed to follow the instructions of the
17 licensed veterinarian, and
18 b. there is sufficient knowledge of the animal or animals
19 by the licensed veterinarian to initiate at least a
20 general or preliminary diagnosis of the medical
21 condition of the animal or animals in that:
22 (1) the licensed veterinarian has recently seen or is
23 personally acquainted with the keeping and care
24 of the animal or animals, or
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 4

1 (2) the licensed veterinarian has made medically
2 necessary and timely visits to the premises where
3 the animal or groups of animals are kept or both
4 maintained and created a herd health plan with
5 the client within the last twelve (12) months,
6 and
7 c. the licensed veterinarian is readily available for
8 follow-up in case of adverse reactions or failure of
9 the regimen of therapy, or has arranged for emergency
10 medical coverage, and
11 d. the licensed veterinarian's actions would conform to
12 applicable federal law and regulations;
13 14. "Veterinary premises" means any facility where the practice
14 of veterinary medicine occurs including, but not limited to, a
15 mobile unit, mobile clinic, outpatient clinic, satellite clinic,
16 public service outreach of a veterinary facility or veterinary
17 hospital or clinic. The term "veterinary premises" shall not
18 include the premises of a client of a licensed veterinarian or
19 research facility;
20 15. "Veterinary prescription drugs" means such prescription
21 items as are in the possession of a person regularly and lawfully
22 engaged in the manufacture, transportation, storage or wholesale or
23 retail distribution of veterinary drugs and the federal Food and
24 Drug Administration-approved human drugs for animals which because
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 5

1 of t heir toxicity or other potential for harmful effects, or method
2 of use, or the collateral measures necessary for use, are labeled by
3 the manufacturer or distributor in compliance with federal law and
4 regulations to be sold only to or on the prescription order or under
5 the supervision of a licensed veterinarian for use in the course of
6 professional practice. Veterinary prescription drugs shall not
7 include over-the-counter products for which adequate directions for
8 lay use can be written;
9 16. "ECFVG certificate" means a certificate issued by the
10 American Veterinary Medical Association Education Commission for
11 Foreign Veterinary Graduates, indicating that the holder has
12 demonstrated knowledge and skill equivalent to that possessed by a
13 graduate of an accredited or approved college of veterinary
14 medicine;
15 17. "Executive Director" means the Executive Director of the
16 State Board of Veterinary Medical Examiners or the authorized
17 representative of such official;
18 18. "Telemedicine" or "telehealth" means the practice of
19 veterinary medicine including diagnosis, consultation, evaluation,
20 treatment, transfer of medical data or exchange of information by
21 means of a two-way, real-time interactive communication between a
22 client or patient and a veterinarian with access to and reviewing
23 the patient's relevant information prior to the telemedicine visit.
24 Telemedicine or telehealth shall not include consultations provided
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 6

1 by t elephone audio-only communication. A veterinarian using
2 telehealth technologies shall take appropriate steps to establish
3 the veterinarian-client-patient relationship by an in-person
4 examination within the last twelve (12) months and conduct all
5 appropriate evaluations and history of the patient consistent with
6 traditional standards of care for the particular patient
7 presentation. A veterinarian shall be licensed, or under the
8 jurisdiction of, the veterinary board of the jurisdiction where the
9 patient is located. The practice of medicine occurs where the
10 patient is located at the time telehealth technologies are used and
11 the relationship may not be established solely by telephone or
12 electronic means;
13 19. "Person" means any individual, firm, partnership,
14 association, joint venture, cooperative, corporation or any other
15 group or combination acting in concert, and whether or not acting as
16 a principal, trustee, fiduciary, receiver or as any other kind of
17 legal or personal representative, or as the successor in interest,
18 assignee, agent, factor, servant, employee, director, officer,
19 fictitious name certificate or any other representative of such
20 person;
21 20. "Food animal" means any mammalian, poultry, fowl, fish or
22 other animal that is raised primarily for human food consumption;
23 21. "Surgery" means the branch of veterinary science conducted
24 under elective or emergency circumstances, which treats diseases,
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 7

1 inju ries and deformities by manual or operative methods including,
2 but not limited to, cosmetic, reconstructive, ophthalmic,
3 orthopedic, vascular, thoracic and obstetric procedures. The
4 provisions in Section 698.12 of this title shall not be construed as
5 surgery;
6 22. "Abandonment" means to forsake entirely or to neglect or
7 refuse to provide or perform the legal obligations for care and
8 support of an animal by its owner, or the owner's agent.
9 Abandonment shall constitute the relinquishment of all rights and
10 claims by the owner to an animal;
11 23. "Animal chiropractic diagnosis and treatment" means
12 treatment that includes vertebral subluxation complex (VSC) and
13 spinal manipulation of nonhuman vertebrates. The term "animal
14 chiropractic diagnosis and treatment" shall not be construed to
15 allow the:
16 a. use of x-rays,
17 b. performing of surgery,
18 c. dispensing or administering of medications, or
19 d. performance of traditional veterinary care;
20 24. "Animal euthanasia technician" means an employee of a law
21 enforcement agency, an animal control agency or animal shelter that
22 is recognized and approved by the Board, who is certified by the
23 Board and trained to administer sodium pentobarbital to euthanize
24 injured, sick, homeless or unwanted domestic pets and other animals;
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 8

1 25. "Teeth floating", as provided by a nonveterinary equine
2 dental care provider, means the removal of enamel points and the
3 smoothing, contouring and leveling of dental arcades and incisors of
4 equine and other farm animals. It shall not include dental
5 procedures on canines and felines;
6 26. "Nonveterinary reproductive services" means nonveterinary
7 services provided by an individual certified by the Board as a
8 nonveterinary reproductive services technician, and involves and
9 shall be limited to nonsurgical embryo transfer in ruminating
10 animals including cattle, sheep, goats, farmed deer and other
11 ruminating exotic animals such as those found in zoos, and may
12 include basic ultrasonography of their ovaries to evaluate the
13 response to embryo-transfer-associated procedures and of the uterus
14 to determine pregnancy by the detection of a heartbeat within the
15 transferred embryo at or greater than twenty-eight (28) days of
16 gestation of such ruminating animals;
17 27. "Embryo transfer" means the biosecure process of inducing
18 increased ovulations within a donor female for the in vivo
19 production of embryos, the flushing of those embryos, collecting,
20 grading and transferring of those embryos to recipient females or
21 the cryopreservation of those embryos for storage and later transfer
22 to recipient females;
23 28. "Animal Technology Advisory Committee" means the advisory
24 committee established by the Board pursuant to Section 698.30b of
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 9

1 this title to advise and make recommendations to the Board regarding
2 any new and evolving technology, procedure, method or practice that
3 may be considered or otherwise designated as an act of animal
4 husbandry that should be included as an act not prohibited in
5 paragraph 1 of Section 698.12 of the Oklahoma Veterinary Practice
6 Act. Reference to the advisory committee in this act shall mean the
7 Animal Technology Advisory Committee;
8 29. "Examination Committee" means the committee established and
9 described in subsection D of Section 698.30a of this title related
10 to nonveterinary reproductive services; and
11 30. "Probable Cause Committee" means the committee consisting
12 of the Board's secretary or treasurer, investigator and attorney to
13 negotiate and settle disputes in accordance with the Oklahoma
14 Veterinary Practice Act;
15 31. "Medical records" means any form of documentation that
16 provides a current and accurate account of a patient or herd history
17 and relevant medical information. Each licensed veterinarian
18 engaged in the practice shall maintain a complete, legible, written
19 or computer-generated record concerning the patient or herd;
20 32. "Relief veterinarian" means a licensed veterinarian who
21 works on a temporary or contract basis, who performs the duties of a
22 full-time veterinarian. He or she is required to maintain accurate
23 medical records that allow another veterinarian to proceed with care
24 and treatment and promote continuity of care for the animal; and
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3239 Page 10

1 33. "Herd health plan" means a documented plan provided by a
2 licensed veterinarian with a veterinarian-client-patient
3 relationship that establishes the treatment and supportive care for
4 a group of animals to enhance a good herd management and optimize
5 animal health and productivity.
6 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
7 Passed the House of Representatives the 24th day of March, 2026.
